{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480703"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:49:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:49:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"97"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"97","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/97"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.01,0.05,0.28,0.64]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"97"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114827"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"97","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/97"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-09-26T01:35:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T17:32:04+09:30","updatedAction":"revised","acceptedAt":"2025-07-01T10:38:07+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-28 10:37:53"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"97"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16432"}},"author":{"data":null},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96831"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"3052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8069"},{"type":"tags","id":"9589"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31621"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41923"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48434"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96831"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114827"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being found wandering and confused in a neighbour\u0027s garden. He has a medical history of alcoholic hepatitis, depression with previous suicidal ideation, recurrent cellulitis, and haematemesis. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears confused and disorientated. His pulse rate is 96/min, blood pressure 110/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. His apex beat is laterally displaced. Neurological examination reveals horizontal gaze nystagmus, absent ankle reflexes, and an ataxic gait with short shuffling steps.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood glucose is 2.8 mmol/L (4.0-8.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral diazepam 20 mg","Intravenous dexamethasone and ceftriaxone","Intravenous 5% dextrose solution","Intravenous thiamine 300 mg","Administer 300mg thiamine IV and 20-50 ml 50% dextrose IV"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy: confusion, ataxia, and ophthalmoplegia (manifesting as nystagmus). The history of chronic alcohol use, which is the most common cause of thiamine deficiency, supports this diagnosis. However, the patient also has symptomatic hypoglycaemia (2.8 mmol/L) which requires immediate correction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister 300mg thiamine IV and 20-50 ml 50% dextrose IV\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate immediate management. The patient has symptomatic hypoglycaemia with confusion, which requires rapid correction with concentrated glucose. Additionally, the clinical features suggest Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy, necessitating immediate thiamine administration. Thiamine should be given before or concurrently with glucose in patients at risk of Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy, as glucose administration can further deplete thiamine stores. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous thiamine\u003C/strong\u003E alone would address the Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy but would not correct the immediate danger of hypoglycaemia. Thiamine is essential in this patient with chronic alcohol use, but must be accompanied by glucose administration to address the low blood sugar.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous 5% dextrose solution\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate for treating symptomatic hypoglycaemia. D5W is usually infused over time and is used for maintenance fluids or mild, non-urgent hypoglycaemia. It will not provide the rapid correction required for symptomatic or severe hypoglycaemia with confusion or altered consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral diazepam\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for alcohol withdrawal, but this patient is not showing signs of withdrawal such as tremor, tachycardia, or agitation. Additionally, it would not address either the hypoglycaemia or Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous dexamethasone and ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for suspected bacterial meningitis, but this patient\u0027s presentation is not consistent with meningitis - there is no headache, neck stiffness, or fever. Furthermore, this treatment would not address the immediate concerns of hypoglycaemia and Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is a persistent myth in emergency medicine that intravenous glucose should not be administered before thiamine in patients with suspected thiamine deficiency, due to the fear of precipitating Wernicke encephalopathy. However, this teaching is not supported by clinical evidence. The concern stems from the theoretical risk that administering glucose in the context of thiamine deficiency could exacerbate neuronal injury by accelerating carbohydrate metabolism, which depends on thiamine-dependent enzymes. While Wernicke encephalopathy has been reported in cases of prolonged carbohydrate administration without thiamine (such as total parenteral nutrition), there are no documented instances where a single bolus of glucose has triggered Wernicke\u0027s. Therefore, in cases of hypoglycaemia, glucose should never be delayed for thiamine administration\u2014rapid correction of hypoglycaemia takes precedence, and thiamine can be given concurrently or shortly after.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Symptomatic hypoglycaemia requires immediate correction with concentrated glucose followed by thiamine in patients with suspected Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy.","The classic triad of Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy (confusion, ataxia, ophthalmoplegia) is present in only one-third of cases.","Chronic alcohol use is the most common cause of thiamine deficiency leading to Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy."],"references":["Sinha S, Kataria A, Kolla BP, et al. Wernicke Encephalopathy - Clinical Pearls. Mayo Clin Proc 2019; 94:1065-72. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31171116/","Wernicke\u2019s encephalopathy. In: Deranged Physiology [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://derangedphysiology.com/main/required-reading/endocrine-intensive-care/Chapter-226/wernickes-encephalopathy","Thiamine deficiency. In: Life in the Fast Lane (LITFL) [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://litfl.com/thiamine-deficiency/","Hoffman RS. Myths of toxicology: thiamine before dextrose? Emergency Medicine News [online]. 2007 Apr;29(4):32\u201333. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://journals.lww.com/em-news/fulltext/2007/04000/myths_of_toxicology__thiamine_before_dextrose.3.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96831"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"97"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96831"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T17:32:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T17:32:04+09:30","number":10,"notes":"Changed the order of the correct answer to mention thiamine before glucose.","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"97"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114827"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16432"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24